{"id":"1403.1539","submitter":"Matthew Hastings","authors":"M. B. Hastings, D. Wecker, B. Bauer, M. Troyer","title":"Improving Quantum Algorithms for Quantum Chemistry","comments":"12 pages, 11 figures; v2: minor corrections and clarifications","journal-ref":"QIC 15, 1 (2015)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present several improvements to the standard Trotter-Suzuki based\nalgorithms used in the simulation of quantum chemistry on a quantum computer.\nFirst, we modify how Jordan-Wigner transformations are implemented to reduce\ntheir cost from linear or logarithmic in the number of orbitals to a constant.\nOur modification does not require additional ancilla qubits. Then, we\ndemonstrate how many operations can be parallelized, leading to a further\nlinear decrease in the parallel depth of the circuit, at the cost of a small\nconstant factor increase in number of qubits required. Thirdly, we modify the\nterm order in the Trotter-Suzuki decomposition, significantly reducing the\nerror at given Trotter-Suzuki timestep. A final improvement modifies the\nHamiltonian to reduce errors introduced by the non-zero Trotter-Suzuki\ntimestep. All of these techniques are validated using numerical simulation and\ndetailed gate counts are given for realistic molecules.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Mar 2014 19:33:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 23 Mar 2014 22:04:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-12-15"}
